  "title": "Prototyping governance means rethinking the individual and societal uses of time",
  "paragraphs": [
    {
      "content": "In the current hackerspaces and liminal environments (Chapter 3), we see a model of prototyping that supports Kairos as experience of improvisation and ad hoc engagements that serve various needs, goals, and values. We will reproduce and formalize this model in the proposal for public and exploratory sandboxes in Chapter 4. Instead of enforcing the status quo of every new infrastructure, dividing society into early adopters (developers and investors) and users or parasites, prototyping in the sandboxes is a struggle to define a common and public good. It is an ongoing experiment and the struggle to preserve time as an open and shared resource that can serve various normative ideals that we can embed in the infrastructures for governance.",
      "summary": "This paragraph discusses how current hackerspaces offer a model for prototyping that encourages improvisation and serves various needs. The author proposes to replicate this model in public and exploratory sandboxes, promoting them as a means to challenge the status quo of new infrastructures and strive for a common good.",
      "questions": [
        "What is the role of prototyping in current hackerspaces?",
        "How does the author propose to formalize this model?",
        "What is the significance of preserving time as an open and shared resource in governance?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To preserve social and personal agency over the future, we must pay attention to time as Kairos in governance, as we do in technology. This means challenging the convergence of politics and governance with technological infrastructures that reduce time to cosmological patterns, data, natural laws, or ontology expressing time as Chronos. To democratize future-making in the sandboxes, we have to insist on engaging the citizens in their futures as a matter of Kairos, an opportunity to change rather than obey predefined structures and commands. In the age of prototypes, citizens are participants and stakeholders in their future, rather than mere users of future infrastructures.",
      "summary": "In this paragraph, the author stresses the need to consider 'time as Kairos' in governance to ensure social and personal agency over the future. They argue for engaging citizens in future-making and see them as participants rather than just users of future infrastructures.",
      "questions": [
        "What does it mean to consider 'time as Kairos' in governance?",
        "How can we democratize future-making in the sandboxes?",
        "What role do citizens play in the age of prototypes?"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
