  "title": "2.0 Genealogy of Algorithmic Rule",
  "paragraphs": [
    {
      "content": "The origins of the myth of automation go back to the anecdotes about Thales of Miletus from the 6th century B.C.E. They capture ambiguous accounts of Thales’ astronomical observations worthy of praise, but also of condemnation for the control over the future that they allow. Thales, according to one of the anecdotes, became a millionaire who turned his knowledge of astronomy and meteorology into a prediction of olive harvest. According to another, he is a loser whose interest in the heavens caused a fall into a ditch. In one of the accounts, his knowledge of time as Chronos, measurable cycles and patterns in nature, leads to a prediction and good fortune. In another, it leads Thales to denounces a society dominated by such predictions that support the rule of merchants and aristocrats who mock his fall.",
      "summary": "This paragraph traces the origins of automation to the stories of Thales of Miletus in 6th century B.C.E. Thales is depicted as both a successful predictor of events due to his astronomical knowledge, and a cautionary figure whose obsession with the heavens led to his downfall.",
      "questions": [
        "Who was Thales of Miletus?",
        "How did Thales use his knowledge of astronomy and meteorology?",
        "What is the significance of Thales' fall in the context of governance and automation?"
      ]
    }
  ]
